name: EinsteinPy
description: EinsteinPy is an open source pure Python package dedicated to problems arising in General Relativity and relativistic physics, such as goedesics plotting for Schwarzschild space-time model, calculation of Schwarzschild radius for any mass given. Features like visualisation of geodesics of curved black holes and 3D visualisations are some of the features which are planned. It is released under the MIT license.

name: magpylib
description: A simple, user friendly Python 3 toolbox for calculating magnetic fields from permanent magnets and current distributions.
description_good_justification:
We have written in detail the use of our tool in our documentation, problems depend on use case since this is basically a calculator.
We address some use cases in our guides.
https://magpylib.readthedocs.io/en/latest
https://magpylib.readthedocs.io/en/latest/_pages/2_guideExamples/
interact_justification:
We are still working on the Contributor's License Agreement but the foundation for PRs and feedback is already in place.
https://magpylib.readthedocs.io/en/latest/_pages/4_contguide/
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>.
contribution_requirements_justification:
We list out our conditions through here, however we are yet to implement an automated linter to check compliance for us.
https://magpylib.readthedocs.io/en/latest/_pages/5_devguide/
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/magpylib/magpylib/blob/master/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The AGPL-3.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The AGPL-3.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).

We have written a lengthy guide and explanation section on understanding and utilizing our API (with Example

https://magpylib.readthedocs.io/en/latest/_pages/2_guideExamples/
https://magpylib.readthedocs.io/en/latest/_pages/3_MATLAB/

version_unique_justification:

We update our version numbers every time before these are uploaded to the package indexes.

release_notes_justification:
We note these in https://github.com/magpylib/magpylib/releases
But these are not included anywhere with the project.
release_notes_vulns_justification: Unless CPython itself has vulnerabilities, our calculator library has no way of causing harm by being used while connected to the internet or otherwise.
report_process_justification:
We have Github Issues with a [BUG] template set up, as well as a contact e-mail.
https://github.com/magpylib/magpylib/issues/new/choose
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Our project is an Offline calculator, vulnerabilities (if even possible) would be treated as bugs.
build_floss_tools_justification: We run numpy and matplotlib as dependencies, which are open-source.
test_invocation_justification: You can run pytest or tox to test our library.
test_most_justification: We have in place +120 tests of core functionalities of our API.
test_policy_justification:
https://magpylib.readthedocs.io/en/stable/_pages/4_contguide/#pull-request-process

tests_are_added_justification: We have not had major releases since the first one.
warnings_justification:

dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: We use assertions for critical inputs that produce illogical results (due to the lack of input checking).
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: Every time we encounter an issue in our Suite pertaining stability we address it immediately.
general_comments: In developing magpylib, which is a tool useful to both Physics Students and Electromagnetic System designers, we have focused heavily on accessibility, maintanability and overall user friendliness in order for it to be as practical as a Python API gets. For this we not only have dedicated a quite a bit of attention into our design, but also into making our Documentation easy to access, edit and utilize.

test_continuous_integration_justificatio: We use CircleCI, AppVeyor and Azure Pipelines to run tests in different environments.

english_justification: Our documentation and codebase is based entirely in the English language.
